<TextWithNodes><Node id="0"/>Manufacturers&apos; warnings about job cuts and shrinking production are spread across the country, including prosperous <Node id="116"/>south-east England<Node id="134"/>, the <Node id="140"/>Confederation of British Industry<Node id="173"/> said on <Node id="182"/>Tuesday<Node id="189"/>.<Node id="190"/>

<Node id="192"/>Publishing a regional breakdown of its regular survey of manufacturers, the <Node id="268"/>CBI<Node id="271"/> said that companies in <Node id="295"/>south-east England<Node id="313"/> and <Node id="318"/>London<Node id="324"/> were the most pessimistic about job prospects over the <Node id="380"/>next four months<Node id="396"/>.<Node id="397"/>

<Node id="399"/>Companies in <Node id="412"/>Scotland<Node id="420"/> seemed the gloomiest about the business situation. <Node id="472"/>Scotland<Node id="480"/>, along with <Node id="493"/>south-east England<Node id="511"/>, has a large number of high-technology companies, and <Node id="566"/>52 per cent<Node id="577"/> of those were pessimistic about the <Node id="614"/>next four months<Node id="630"/>.<Node id="631"/>

<Node id="633"/>Peter Gutmann<Node id="646"/>, associate director of the consultancy <Node id="686"/>Business Strategies<Node id="705"/>, which helped produce the survey, said the results implied further job losses of 29,000 in manufacturing <Node id="811"/>between July and September<Node id="837"/>.<Node id="838"/>

<Node id="840"/>&quot;Previously resilient regions are experiencing the pain as much as traditional manufacturing areas, as the downturn has affected new technology sectors,&quot; he said.<Node id="1002"/>

<Node id="1004"/>The effect of any such job cuts on consumer confidence has been identified by economists as one of the key economic relationships in the <Node id="1141"/>second half of the year<Node id="1164"/> that will determine future movements in interest rates.<Node id="1220"/>

<Node id="1222"/>On <Node id="1225"/>Wednesday<Node id="1234"/>, the <Node id="1240"/>Bank of England<Node id="1255"/> publishes its quarterly inflation report, including the forecasts for inflation over the <Node id="1345"/>next two years<Node id="1359"/>. Formerly the highlight of the monetary policy process in the <Node id="1422"/>UK<Node id="1424"/>, the inflation reports have faded somewhat from prominence as divisions on the monetary policy committee have made the formulation of a unified forecast increasingly difficult.<Node id="1601"/>

<Node id="1603"/>But <Node id="1607"/>City<Node id="1611"/> economists said <Node id="1628"/>Wednesday<Node id="1637"/>&apos;s report would be eagerly awaited by investors and commentators looking for an explanation for the <Node id="1737"/>Bank<Node id="1741"/>&apos;s surprise interest rate cut <Node id="1771"/>last week<Node id="1780"/>. In the past, the committee has not been more likely to move rates in the month it produces the inflation forecast.<Node id="1896"/>

<Node id="1898"/>&quot;The monetary policy committee seems to be looking at the question the other way round,&quot; said <Node id="1992"/>Ciaran Barr<Node id="2003"/>, <Node id="2005"/>UK<Node id="2007"/> economist at <Node id="2021"/>Deutsche Bank<Node id="2034"/> in <Node id="2038"/>London<Node id="2044"/>. &quot;Instead of worrying that consumer demand was outpacing the rest of the economy, they are now asking: what happens if confidence falls and consumer spending slows down?<Node id="2214"/>

<Node id="2216"/>&quot;The catalyst for this change of view may well have been sitting down and crunching the numbers for the inflation forecast.&quot;<Node id="2340"/>

<Node id="2342"/>However, definitive conclusions about the thinking of the committee may have to wait until <Node id="2433"/>next week<Node id="2442"/> when the minutes of <Node id="2463"/>last week<Node id="2472"/>&apos;s meeting are released.<Node id="2496"/>

<Node id="2498"/>Last August<Node id="2509"/>, markets were reassured by the dovish tone taken by <Node id="2562"/>Mervyn King<Node id="2573"/>, the Bank&apos;s deputy governor, when he was presenting the inflation report, only to be surprised a week later when it emerged that <Node id="2703"/>Mr King<Node id="2710"/> and three other committee members had voted for higher interest rates.<Node id="2781"/>

<Node id="2783"/>Some economists have suggested that <Node id="2819"/>last week<Node id="2828"/>&apos;s vote may not have been unanimous either. During <Node id="2879"/>last month<Node id="2889"/>&apos;s <Node id="2892"/>MPC<Node id="2895"/> meeting, the committee threw the markets off guard by saying that &quot;for some the news [over the month] made it less likely that the next move in interest rates would be down&quot;.<Node id="3070"/>
